  "eprint": {
    "title": "The Age of Testifying Wearable Devices: The Case of Intoxication Detection",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Ben Nassi",
        "email": "nassiben5@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Lior Rokach",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Yuval Elovici",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "Seven years ago, a famous case in which data from a Fitbit tracker was used in the courtroom in a personal injury case heralded a new age: the age of testifying wearable devices.\nPrior to that, data from wearable devices was used in various areas, including medicine, advertising, and scientific research, but the use of such data in the Fitbit case attracted the interest of a new sector: the legal sector.\nSince then, lawyers, investigators, detectives, and police officers have used data from pacemakers and smartwatches in order to prove/disprove allegations regarding wearable device owners in several well-known cases (sexual assault, arson, personal injury, etc.).\nIn this paper, we discuss testifying wearable devices.\nWe explain the advantages of wearable devices over traditional IoT devices in the legal setting, the parties involved in cases in which a wearable device was used to testify against/for the device owner, and the information flow.\nWe then focus on an interesting area of research: intoxication detection.\nWe explain the motivation to detect whether a subject was intoxicated and explain the primary scientific gap in this area.\nIn order to overcome this gap, we suggest a new method for detecting whether a subject was intoxicated based on free gait data obtained from a wearable device.\nWe evaluate the performance of the proposed method in a user study involving 30 subjects and show that motion sensor data obtained from a smartphone and fitness tracker from eight seconds of free gait can indicate whether a subject is/was intoxicated (obtaining an AUC of 0.97) and thus be used as testimony.\nFinally, we analyze the current state and the near future of the age of testifying wearable devices and explain why we believe that (1) we are still at the beginning of this age despite the fact that seven years has passed since the original court case, and (2) the number of cases in which wearable device data is used to testify for/against the device owner is expected to increase significantly in the next few years.",
    "keywords": [
      "privacy",
      "IoT devices"
    ],
